segments.text: an interview with Tom Rugg, conducted by David White, Texas A&M University, on April the 22nd, 1989.
Now, we had stopped off with the spring of 1968 and Tet, and you concluded by saying that you had definite feelings at the time, but nothing really now, correct?
Well, it was nothing.
I had no specific recollection of
what the Tet Offensive meant or didn't mean to me at the time.
I just don't recall that now.
I recall you said that you thought that what we were doing over there was wrong.
Was it just our foreign policy was wrong, or did you feel that how we were conducting our foreign policy was wrong, or was it something else entirely?
No, I guess it was both.
I did not think then, and I have seen nothing to change my mind in the years that have passed to the present time, that we had any business in Vietnam, period.
However, the country often does things that some of the people of the country don't agree with.
In fact, that's just sort of the nature of the beast.
If we were going to be there,
then it was just incomprehensible to me that the war would be managed in such a way that we couldn't possibly win it or achieve a military objective.
And it was also apparent that that was going on.
So it really made no sense.

First of all, I disagreed with being there, but if we were going to be there, then let's at least let the military people manage the war in such a way that they can achieve a military objective, whatever the hell that was going to be, if they wanted to own all of Southeast Asia, whatever the military objective was going to be.
Let the guys who know how to achieve that objective go and do it, and don't put artificial barriers on them and tell them, well, you can do this or you can't do that.
That's where a part of all that insanity of Agent Orange came up with.
It was neat.
We can't fight a jungle war because we don't know how, and we're not going to train or learn how, apparently, so we'll kill the jungle.
Well, it's insanity, just absolute insanity.
But that's the kind of things that were going on.
You said that they should be free to...

fight what war they wanted to yeah if you're gonna if you're going to allow the country to become involved in a war then first of all let's call it a war let's have the congress declare war and let's let the military people go win it if that's what the policy of the country is going to be

And I don't have to agree with that individually that that's what the policy ought to be, but if that's what the leadership of the country says we're going to do, then let's don't fight the war in such a way that we're guaranteed to lose it and that we're going to maximize our casualties and that it's going to be as crippling as it can be, that it's going to go on forever and ever with no definable objectives being obtained or even being talked about such that it tears this country apart internally.
That war went on forever.
Incredibly long period of time.
With no popular support after we'd been in the war for a while.
You know, the Vietnam War protest didn't start from day one.
It's after it went on and on and on.
And our commitment to it got more and more and more and more people were being killed.
and it became more and more obvious that the war was being fought in such a way that it could not be won, then lots of people started asking questions like, what in the hell are we doing there?
I mean, that didn't start from the beginning.
That was a period of time.
It was just a total and mismanaged process.
Now, had you been president at the time,
Just have withdrawn the troops totally, or would you have let them go off to fight their own war?
Oh, I'd have withdrawn the troops.
Definitely.
Yeah, I wouldn't have had them there in the first place.
I'd have ended up where Richard Nixon ended up after we killed a half million people and maimed millions of others and put emotional scars on people who never went there.
Yeah, I'd have never gone through that process.
It was in sight.
You know, what has this country lost by not having a military presence in Vietnam, and we haven't had one for a long time?
Nothing.
We had no reason to be there to begin with.
Talk about Richard Nixon.
So you would say by the, you know, 68 was an election year.
You would say that by the end of the summer you were beginning to formulate opinions about who you wanted for president, or were you even concerned about voting?
Oh, yeah.
I don't think I've ever missed an election.
I vote in the local elections.
In fact, I've got to vote absentee.
I'm going to be out of town when the local elections come up here in another two weeks.
Yeah, I was very much interested in who was going to be president and not going to be president back in those years.
And, of course, the main issue, I guess, was Vietnam.
Certainly, from my perspective, the foreign policy was really the dominant issue because of Vietnam.
Were you inclined to lean towards one candidate or another?
I didn't see, no, I really wasn't.
There wasn't a candidate around that I liked.
You know, Richard Nixon pulled out of Vietnam because there was no other alternative.
I mean, they were totally beat militarily before they left.
Nobody was advocating that we pull out, which was my preference.
And ultimately what happened in terms of our disinvolvement in Vietnam was inevitable.
It was just a question of who happened to be in the White House when it occurred it was going to happen.
Do you remember Chicago that summer?
I remember the news accounts of it, and I remember that it would have been a neat place to have been.
I would like to have been there.
Would you have taken part actively?
Yeah, you betcha.
I really would have.
I'd have enjoyed that.
That would have been fun.
Did you look up to any of the people who were eventually quote-unquote charged with inciting the riot, like...
Hoffman or any of those other people?
No, I didn't have any idols that I followed around during those years.
None of the names were important to me.
It was the issues.
I didn't care about who the media selected to be the stars or who the spokesmen were.
It was the issues from my perspective.
For whom did you end up voting for president that year and why?
I don't even remember.
I honestly do not remember.
I really didn't feel that there was, I didn't feel like it made any difference, that there was a real choice.
And I can't remember who I voted for.
In the fall of 68, did you notice any increasing activism on campus or were you still pretty much apathetic?
I can't remember.
I really cannot remember levels of campus activity tied with any particular time period.
Well, can you remember any specific protests on campus?
Not that I could give you details of.
I know there were some.
Didn't seem like there was a lot of organization in anti-war feelings.
And there seemed to be.
Again, more organization out at Lamar when we got into funds that were racially oriented.
I can remember a couple of pretty good-sized demonstrations that involved racial issues, and I really don't remember
organized sizable demonstrations involving Vietnam, which is not to say there weren't any.
There just aren't any that I remember that stick out in my mind.
Were any of the racial demonstrations linked to Vietnam over, say, the number of black troops that were getting killed compared to the white troops?
No.
In fact, I'm not even sure when I became aware of the racial disparity in the way assignments
well, in the draft generally, but in assignments particularly to Vietnam areas.

I know that, and it may have been after I got out of college that I first became aware that blacks were being assigned in disproportionate numbers to the Vietnam War effort and were suffering naturally as a result of that, disproportionately high casualties.
relative to their proportion of the population in this country.
I mean, there's some pretty obvious reasons for that.
Would you say then that, in general, the students down here were more concerned with issues closer to home than some more often in Asia?
Yeah.
See, I don't even remember any big war protests cranking up
after the lottery system came out, student deferments were going to be a thing of history, and if your number was bad, you were up.

And you would have thought, if anything, that that would have cranked it up, that that would have really started the effort, the war protesting effort, particularly for those who were going to be targets of the draft and who had low numbers.
But those people just kind of disappeared.
They went off to war is what happened to them.
What were you doing in 1970?
Were you still in school?
Oh, yeah.
I didn't graduate from Lamar until 1972.
Well, I spent six years in undergraduate school, but I was a student most of that time and had 170-some-odd undergraduate hours.
And because you had that low lottery number and in French you declared 4F,
Yeah, the war, so far as me personally, it was obvious that I wasn't going to be able to go if I wanted to go.
Even if you enlisted?
I couldn't enlist.
4F, you don't enlist anywhere.
I wouldn't go into the war.
Now, just to clarify, this is for the Army, correct?
Well, selective service, they were just drafting into the Army.
You had long lines of people trying to get into more favorable forms of service.
who otherwise knew they were going to get drafted.
Such as National Guard or Navy?
Oh, yeah.
Those people weren't having much trouble getting recruits.
The foot soldier was the guy who was being drafted.
If all had ever occurred to you that if you had been drafted, you might have been sent to someplace like Europe?
Certainly possible, I have.
I had some friends who went to Germany and Europe.
During that time?
Yeah.
How did they feel?
I know some of them were happy to be in Europe and had done everything possible within the workings of the Army to ensure that they went anywhere other than Vietnam.
So they were quite happy with themselves.
Yeah.
Well, people who are career military tend to be fairly satisfied with the Army, the short-timers.
one-term enlisted folks.
You don't run across many of them who speak glowingly of military service.
But they were certainly pleased that their duty assignment didn't put them in Vietnam.
Do you remember hearing about the U.S. involvement in Cambodia?
Yeah.
Cambodia and Laos both.
And it seems like the mayor will remember that the media made a
a big deal out of it.
Of course, they'd like to do that anyway, but they uncovered these excursions into Vietnam that we didn't have the permission of, excuse me, the incursions into Cambodia.
We didn't have the permission of the Cambodia government to be there.
It violated all sorts of laws and international laws to go do things like that.
and the news media made a real big event of having uncovered it.
And, of course, the government, of course, was denying it.
The government had so very little credibility with me at that point in time that I could have written the scripts for them.
They denied everything.
If it was bad, they denied it.
If it was good, they patted themselves on the back.
Were you better at the government for lying to you?
I think disillusion is a better term.
I don't then and I do not now understand why the government feel like it is necessary to deliberately deceive the people who put them in power.
I don't understand that attitude.
It is an attitude that some political leaders are afflicted with.
My view is they tend to be concentrated in one particular party.
particular political bias that I happen to hold.
And I suppose it's not fair to make fun of the Republicans who've had some unfortunate... Don't go ahead if you feel that way.
They've had some people of unfortunate character at the head of their party.
People whose character could not even be described as questionable anymore.
They were downright dishonest.
And I do not understand...
why people of power feel like it is necessary to lie, deceive, and mislead those who've put them there.
That's a betrayal of trust which they've been granted, and those kind of people are very disillusioning to me.
Because the political process does not guarantee that that kind of person rises to the top, you understand.
It has happened.
And it disillusions people with the political process generally, and it shouldn't because that's not a necessary outcome of the political process.
So by the spring of 72, for example, you were just feeling pretty much the government can go shove its head in the sand or something like that?
Yeah.
Of course, the spring of 72 is my graduation time.
I'm going to graduate from Lamar as a university, first May graduating class after Lamar attained university status, and I don't have a job.
And the prospects for getting one, well, I have a job.
I'm working at a job I could have had with a high school education.
I'm working in an automobile trim shop and continued to do that job after I graduated.
I looked around a little bit, looked for some of the jobs you could get with them.
a business degree and didn't really like any of it.
What were your feelings in 72 when the elections came around?
Were you satisfied with what Nixon was doing?
Or did you feel it was a crock?
Oh, I never did like Nixon.
He was just not a favorite of mine.
And still isn't.
Did you feel that he was doing a good job of getting the troops out of Asia, or was he just doing what he had to do in order to keep from losing all face?
He was doing what he was.
We were beat.
I mean, I realize it wasn't necessarily being portrayed that way, but they were leaving Vietnam.
It was either leave or die.
Those were not good options at that point in time.
We were beat.
We've been losing the war for years.
Sooner or later, you're going to have to concede defeat.
That's all that was going on.
He didn't deserve any pat on the back for doing what he had to do.
It was long since past time to wave the white flag.
He doesn't get any kudos from me for doing what was inevitable.
Did he or any of the other presidents do anything that ever got you thinking to say, hey, maybe I better get out on the streets and protest?
Well, let's see.
The last time I was on the streets was when the Iranians took over our embassy.
No, I think it.
By 1972, it was time for me to start getting on with my life and planning on going somewhere.
You know, the war was a dead issue by then, and it was time to move on, time to figure out something to do, some sort of a career to follow.
So when the Christmas bombings came in 1972, you just kind of sighed in resignation?
I don't even remember that.
I don't have any recollection of that at all.
Except 1975, Vietnam fell.
What do you remember about that?
I remember, it seems like the news media had quite a heyday with the panic scenes at Saigon airport.
And it seems to me that I recall thinking that it is long since past time that we got out of there.
And that this is not gonna result in any great upheaval or turmoil or chaos in the rest of Southeast Asia.
Unlike the people who were predicting the doom and the eventual fall in the entire world as we know it.
we lost this little tiny thing called Vietnam.
I had determined before that that was just a bunch of baloney anyway.
Really very anticlimactic, I guess, for me.
To digress a bit, you were in college during that time.
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.
68 through 72 when we seem now to make so much about, oh, that was the age of Aquarius and all this stuff that they would call counterculture.
What were your recollections of that?
I'm not sure there was a lot of counterculture going on in Beaumont from 68 to 72.
That was something that was going on out on the west coast, I thought.
And that's
That's really about as close to that as I got.
I wasn't having to do it.
There was a bunch of nuts out on the west coast.
So you'd say pretty much here that we were concerned more with what was around us than what was not around us.
Well, no, I don't think that's necessarily fair either.
I think my generation
was somewhat, and this is true and was true generally everywhere I was, is that my generation honestly did not trust the generation above us, our parents' generation, their leaders.
That was true for me and was true, I think, for a lot of people.
The more vocal and sometimes violent parts of that occurred in other places and were media events.

But I honestly believe that my generation genuinely did not, as a whole, and certainly that's not true for everybody, but as a general rule, genuinely distrusted and disliked the generation that preceded us who was then in power.
And I think we
could build a pretty good case for feeling that way.
Do you really blame Vietnam on any one person besides, well, you seem to have an insubordination towards Nixon.
Are there any other people or persons that you would single out in your mind?
No, Vietnam, let's see, that can't happen.
One person couldn't do a Vietnam.
It takes a collection of people in power, but it takes a collective attitude on the part of a country that really doesn't care and isn't paying attention to what's going on to get you into Vietnam.
And that's why I don't think you've seen the repeat of that in areas like Honduras, for example.
where at least in a geographical sense, it would make a lot more sense to have an American military presence in Honduras than Vietnam.
But you don't see that.
And yet all you've got there is an internal civil war, basically between sort of democracy-oriented people and sort of communistic-oriented people.
And it's a fundamental civil war we have going on.
and one that's the Vietnam story.
And you can't blame any one person for us getting involved in that.
It's a national mistake.
I'm sure that the people who got in there did not get into Vietnam thinking, boy, isn't this going to be fun to have a national disaster.
Obviously, I think there were men with good intentions who were wrong,
in a country that wasn't paying attention until when the country did start paying attention, then it was a very long, slow, painful process to get out of the mistake we'd gotten ourselves into.
What did you end up doing after you received your undergraduate degree?
I worked for a year and then enrolled in law school at the University of Texas.
You didn't view law school as any sort of compromising any ideals that you had?
Yeah, law's a profession.
You can do anything you want to with a law degree.
You don't have to be involved in government.
You can be a wild ass independent ACLU type of person, or you can go to work in Washington.
The whole world is up until you were alone.
If you had been born 20 years earlier so that in 1968 you would be as old as you are now.
You mean if I had been born 20 years later?
20 years earlier.
20 years earlier than 48?
That would be 1928?
Okay.
I would have just missed World War II.
Obviously.

Knowing having enough world knowledge as you do now, meaning that in 1968 you were a fairly mature person, law degree, fairly successful, established practice, do you think you would have felt the same way about the wars you did then?
Probably not.
As you get over and you get more established and set in your ways, it tends to be a little bit more difficult to get you stirred up and riled up.
But I can't say for sure.
I know the way I feel today, if someone were to suggest that an American military presence in Honduras was a good idea, you'd never be able to sell me on that one.
But that might be because of the Vietnam experience.
I don't know.
Very difficult times.
You're coming off of Korea, which was, I guess you could call it a draw, but sort of this multinational exercise in killing people in Korea.
In itself, a very interesting war from a historical perspective.
But you don't have a whole nation protesting your involvement.
It's a relatively short war and results in, I guess, a more or less satisfactory negotiated solution.
It's certainly much different than the Vietnam result.
So you wouldn't have in your own makeup a historical perspective of what's going on.
To a certain extent, I guess you could justify the Korean War involvement as a part of our responsibility to the United Nations, which was then and still is a pretty novel experiment.
But at least it gives countries a forum where they can yell at each other.
Do you think the UN should have gotten involved at all in NOM?
Run that one by me again.
Do you think that the U.N. should have been called in in Vietnam?
No.
Of course they couldn't because of their system.
The system, the way it worked, it wasn't realistically possible for the United Nations to get involved.
They'd never gotten involved in Korea.
Russia hadn't got the red ass and walked out of a Security Council meeting.
They learned that lesson.
So there wasn't any realistic chance of the United Nations getting involved in Vietnam.
You might have had a very much different solution if that had happened.

Certainly, you would have had a little more collective military wisdom involved, and you would have had a very different political leadership involved as opposed to the President of the United States, chief commander of the war effort in Vietnam, you'd have had.
entirely different political setup out of the United Nations, saying, you know, it might have made a world of difference, but I don't think it would have necessarily made it right.
You know, I suppose if these countries want to get together and have civil wars, they ought to let them do it.
You know, we did one here.
And the country survived and rolled on.
Vietnam has survived and rolled on.
Their political leadership may be one that we've all been told we're not supposed to like.
But I don't know.
They work fine for them.
If Vietnam, instead of being some nation halfway across the globe, had instead been some little island about 500 miles off Galveston, do you think our attitudes would have been any different?
I think that might have affected some people.
But it shouldn't.
We've had Cuba 90 miles off the coast of Florida for a long time.
So the big fear is, oh, my God, the communists will be too close.
They'll be able to hit us with missiles.
Well, who are you kidding?
They can hit us from central interior Russia.
So that doesn't make any difference.
No, it shouldn't make a difference.
It probably would for some people.
If there was one thing in your mind that you could have changed about that whole era, what would it have been?
You mean me personally?
You personally.
Me personally?
And then for the nation.
Yeah, I don't know.
That's a tough one, me personally.
I'm not really unhappy with my life as it went through those years.
I would like to have not...

particularly in high school, have had to go to so many different high schools and so many different places and constantly have to start over, knowing no one, and have to start over building new friends only to leave them all and go on and do that again.
That's not fun.
I would want to do that again, and I won't do that to my children.
I'll find a different line of work, although I'm very stable now.
What about for the nation?
The nation, they should have walked away from Vietnam when they were invited.
They just said, no, we're not going to do that.
The French couldn't make it work.
We don't think we're any better at it than they are.
You folks over there in that part of the world need to sort this out on your own.
I see.
Well, that concludes this interview.
I want to thank you for taking time out of your schedule.
And again, this is going into the...
The Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
And that's it.
Thank you very much.
Thank you.
